And the wall collapsed …
Here's a quiz for history buffs: twenty years ago, in 1989, it was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4.
Which one do you remember best and which had the heaviest consequences for the planet?
a) The bloody suppression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few people respond with c).
Because the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and consequently to the post-war international order's reorganization.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory that came out of nowhere.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern bloc since the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader in charge of Poland, General Jaruzelski, thought that the country's economic problems were too severe for him to face alone.
Why not call on the Polish opposition, he thought - if not to find a solution - at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of negotiations, he concluded a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarnosc would be able to participate.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) never for a moment thought they could lose.
Not even in their darkest nightmares did they imagine they would be driven out of power.
Yet, that is what happened.
Looking back, it is astonishing that there could have been any doubts.
Solidarnosc ran its campaign boldly.
A famous poster, taken out of context for the occasion, a classic western movie poster, The Great Dictator, had great success: it shows Gary Cooper holding a ballot box instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4 was the day of judgment.
On that sunny Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one final perversity that turned into an involuntary humiliation.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to cross out the names of those they didn't want - essentially all the communists listed on the ballots.
Wherever you looked, people were getting rid of the detested autocrats.
This was finally the long-awaited popular uprising in Poland, the revenge for December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarnosc, and threw its leaders in prison.
The revolution by ballot!
Skilledly wielded, the pen that ultimately triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious vengeance.
Certain voters were tearing up their ballots completely, effectively decapitating the old regime with a single stroke.
Others were savoring the moment, maybe smoking a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one, he put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "Look, this apparatchik got rich on our shortage," Pfft!
Pfft!
However, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
Across all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most relied on the monopoly they had in the media to get their message across: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist".
One can give credit to the regime for acknowledging its defeat with remarkable graciousness.
The day after the elections, at three in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the party's top leaders to tell them: "Our defeat is total," we need to find a political solution".
This meant that he did not want either violence or fraud, the communists would have to live with the result of the vote.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us who covered Eastern Europe knew that Solidarnosc would win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern Bloc.
The election in Poland was extremely encouraging for anti-communists all around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began to dismantle the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European House" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet, when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming".
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom burst forth.
